@node IML-145 " MSG-145  Subject: Sorry Could Not Find Subject!
@toc contents

Date:    Monday, 19 December 1994 22:04:19 
From:    imagine-relay@email.sp.paramax.com


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  


On Sun, 18 Dec 1994, Jon Bagge wrote:
> 
> Two boxes bound by bars.  The x'es marks joints.
> 
>        XOOX
>        !  !
>        !  !
>        !  !
>        !  ! 
>        XOOX
> 
>   XOOX
>    \  \
>     \  \
>      \  \
>       XOOX
>
[lots of stuff deleted]

I created an animation of a hydraulic backhoe and encountered similar 
problems.  I worked around the problem by anchoring the base of each 
piston to the assembly, then rotated each piston after I repositioned the 
arm assembly.  One section looks like this:

XOOX   <-anchored to assembly at this point
 \   \ 
  \    \
   \     \  <-this point free. rotate and move in or out (or resize) 
    XOOX

I know this isn't an ideal arrangement but I did get it to work.  In the 
final animation the pistons looked fine - no movement where there 
shouldn't have been.  I used about 4 states for each transition.
Hope this helps.

Ed Totman
etotman@gort.ucsd.edu


 

